ork on the subject for an English audience. It explores the presence of magical elements in everyday life during the modern period in Spain. The book provides a general overview of vernacular magical beliefs and practices in Italy from the time of unification to the present, with particular attention to how these traditions have been studied. By functioning as mechanisms of social ethos and control, narratives of magical harm were assured a place at the very heart of rural Finnish social dynamics into the twentieth century. The book draws upon over 300 narratives recorded in rural Finland in the late nineteenth and early twentieth centuries that provide information concerning the social relations, tensions and strategies that framed sorcery and the counter-magic employed against it. It is concerned with a special form of witchcraft that is practised only amongst Hungarians living in Transylvania.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aWitchcraftzEuropexHistoryy19th century. 0aWitchcraftzEuropexHistoryy20th century. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh  aEngland.  aEurope.  aFinland.  aFrance.  aGermany.  aItaly.  aNetherlands.  aSpain.  amagical harm.  apopular magic.  avernacular magical beliefs.  avernacular magical practices.  awitchcraft.1 aDavies, Owen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDavies, Owen, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDe Blecourt, Willem, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aFreytag, Nils, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHoyle, Susan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJenkins, Richard, econtri